The paper discusses the development of a library for I/O-efficient algorithms, which suggests that it belongs to the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The library is specifically designed for handling large datasets that exceed the capacity of main memory, which is a common problem in database systems (cs.DB). The paper also discusses the pipelining framework for streaming-based implementations, which is a topic related to parallel and distributed computing (cs.DC) and concurrency theory (cs.CC). Finally, the library is used for commercial terrain processing applications, which suggests a connection to computational geometry (cs.CG) and programming languages (cs.PL) for implementing such applications.
